8bt.title: Preemptive Learning
8bt.clickbait: One of the basic theorems of logical inductors, used to derive many other theorems that rely on "buy low, sell high" strategies.
8bt.text:
If $\overline{A}\in\mathcal{BCS}(\overline{\mathbb{P}})$, then $\text{lim inf}_{n\to\infty}\mathbb{P}_{n}(A_{n})=\text{lim inf}_{n\to\infty}\text{sup}_{m\ge n}\mathbb{P}_{m}(A_{n})$ and $\text{lim sup}_{n\to\infty}\mathbb{P}_{n}(A_{n})=\text{lim sup}_{n\to\infty}\text{inf}_{m\ge n}\mathbb{P}_{m}(A_{n})$

%%hidden(What's BCS(P)?):
It's the set of all sequences of $\mathbb{R}$-combinations (bundles of cash and shares), that are $\overline{\mathbb{P}}$-generable (There's a sequence of $\mathcal{EF}$-combinations that can be written down in poly-time that will turn into the $\mathbb{R}$-combinations given market data), and bounded (there's some $b$ such that the L1 norm, the sum of the absolute value of the coefficients, is $\le b$.)

These sound like weird conditions to impose, but $\mathbb{R}$-combinations can be used to encode constraints between sentences like "3 of these 7 sentences are true" and "A xor B" by having the $\mathbb{R}$-combination for those sentences have a value of 3, and 1, respectively.

The $\overline{\mathbb{P}}$-generable condition is important to impose so the trader is actually able to *write down* the combination in the first place to trade with it.

The "boundedness" part is mainly useful to scale down an unruly sequence so the magnitude of each combination is 1 or less, to make it feasible to analyze.

Because of these essential properties, $\mathcal{BCS}(\mathbb{P})$ could be thought of as the set of $\mathbb{R}$-combination-sequences it's actually possible to prove stuff about and that the logical inductor can feasibly analyze. It will be showing up in most future theorems.
%%

## Basic Intuition ##

Imagine a giant grid, with the index of the $\mathbb{R}$-combinations on the $x$-axis, and the day on the $y$-axis. Imagine it as a landscape where the elevation at a spot is the value of the combination on a particular day. 

We'll be walking along the diagonal, in this particular case. Imagine there's a series of signs along that diagonal, that list the greatest and least elevation/value you'd ever reach if you just walked north forever. (this corresponds to $\text{sup}_{m\ge n}\mathbb{P}_{m}(A_{n})$ and $\text{inf}$, respectively) What this theorem says is that if you walk along the diagonal, the asymptotic lower bound on the elevation/value is the same as the asymptotic lower bound of the "greatest elevation to the north/greatest future value" advertised on the series of signs. Similarly, the asymptotic upper bound on the elevation/value is the same as the asyptotic upper bound of the "lowest elevation to the north/lowest future value"

Put another way, the "asymptotic lower bound of greatest future value" and "asymptotic upper bound of lowest future value" eventually get projected back into bounds on the value of the combinations along the diagonal. This links the far-distant values of combinations back to their "immediate" values along the diagonal, if we wait long enough.

## Proof Formulation ##

Well, since we've already proved the [88p], we can get away with assuming that preemptive-learning property is false, and then showing that it lets us fulfill the four $\varepsilon$-ROI lemma prerequisites that'll result in a contradiction with the assumption that we have a logical inductor.

As a recap, they are as follows:

 - $\varepsilon$-ROI on all "employees"
 - The sequence of "employees" is efficiently emulatable so they can be combined into a "trading firm"
 - There is a $\overline{\mathbb{P}}$-generable sequence $\overline\alpha$ that describes the magnitude of the sequence of "employees"
 - $\displaystyle lim_{k\to\infty}\alpha_{k}\neq 0$.

What would happen if the preemptive learning property, $\text{lim inf}_{n\to\infty}\mathbb{P}_{n}(A_{n})=\text{lim inf}_{n\to\infty}\text{sup}_{m\ge n}\mathbb{P}_{m}(A_{n})$ was false?

Well, straightaway, $\text{sup}_{m\ge n}\mathbb{P}_{m}(A_{n})\ge\mathbb{P}_{n}(A_{n})$. So if it's going to fail at all, it must be because $\text{lim inf}_{n\to\infty}\mathbb{P}_{n}(A_{n})<\text{lim inf}_{n\to\infty}\text{sup}_{m\ge n}\mathbb{P}_{m}(A_{n})$.

This means that there's a gap, so there's some $b$ and some $\varepsilon>0$ where $\text{lim inf}_{n\to\infty}\mathbb{P}_{n}(A_{n})<b-\varepsilon<b+\varepsilon<\text{lim inf}_{n\to\infty}\text{sup}_{m\ge n}\mathbb{P}_{m}(A_{n})$.

This suggests the buy low, sell high strategy for the employees. Buy an $\mathbb{R}$-combination when its starting price along the diagonal is $b-\varepsilon$ or less, and resell it when its price inevitably goes above $b+\varepsilon$, and pick up a little bit of guaranteed cash for $\varepsilon$-ROI.

There's problems with this, of course. You can't have a sharp cutoff-function for buying and selling, you have to use the continuous indicator functions. Also, the price will only "inevitably" go above $b+\varepsilon$ in the limit. Let's analyze it a bit more, until a path reveals itself.

So, for infinitely many $n$, $\mathbb{P}_{n}(A_{n})<b-\varepsilon$ by the definition of lim inf.

And there's *some* far-distant day $s_{e}$ where $\forall n>s_{e}:\text{sup}_{m\ge n}\mathbb{P}_{n}(A_{n})>b+\varepsilon$.

%%hidden(Wait, what?):
Lets say it was false, then. Then $\forall s_{e}\exists n>s_{e}:\text{sup}_{m\ge n}\mathbb{P}_{n}(A_{n})\le b+\varepsilon$. Or, put another way, there would be infinitely many $n$ where the greatest future value is $b+\varepsilon$ or less. Oh wait, by the definition of lim inf, lim inf(greatest future value) would be $b+\varepsilon$ or less. But it's greater than $b+\varepsilon$, and thus, a contradiction.
%%

Hm... that means that our "trading firm" could just output "employees" that'll do nothing, until day $s_{e}$. Past that point, *every* combination is going to go above $b+\varepsilon$ value, *eventually*. So, let's say you've got an indicator to just start buying if it's at $b-\frac{\varepsilon}{2}$ value, and go all-in at $b-\varepsilon$, and an indicator to just start selling if it's at $b+\frac{\varepsilon}{2}$ value, and sell it all at $b+\varepsilon$. Then since it's guaranteed to go above $b+\varepsilon$ *eventually*, each trader's going to end up unloading everything it bought, and get $\varepsilon$ guaranteed cash. That takes care of the first condition, the $\varepsilon$-ROI one. (not really, we'll flesh it out more later.) 

The second condition about being able to emulate the traders also looks fairly simple if we can define a "percent of original purchase left" feature, since a "sell the thing if the price goes too low" trigger is pretty easy to implement.

The third condition about being able to emulate the magnitude of the employees using market data can be fulfilled without too much trouble, too. Since all the employees will end up selling back everything they bought by the argument for point 1, the magnitude is twice as big as the magnitude of the original trade. Just sum up whatever expressible features were used to make the original trade and bam, you've got an expressible feature that'll produce the magnitude of the employee when exposed to market data. (the expressible features of the first trade can be written down in $poly(k)$ time, remember)

The fourth condition is trivially taken care of by that "infinitely often" clause about how often the value of the combinations dips below $b-\varepsilon$ on the diagonal.

(to be continued)
